        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We will observe TVLM513 using band 3 of ALMA. We will use the default settings for band 3 and observatory suggested calibrations. As TVLM513 is a point source we require an angular resolution of 2".

Figure 2 shows that band 3 is where the strongest emission is likely to occur for a plasma emitting from an object with a magnetic field ranging from 100 to 4 kG. Objects with the weakest field (~100 G) have an estimated flux of 0.1 mJy with objects of a field of 1 kG at 20 mJy. 

We will observe for one rotation of TVLM513 (~2 hours). Because TVLM513 is a known radio emitter at lower frequencies, we will be able to determine if the band 3 measurement is constant, as we would expect, or pulsed, indicating another mechanism related to the electron cyclotron maser instability is involved.

Because we want to monitor the target for one rotation, we have written the planned observations to reflect this.

</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
